  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. Key requirements typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identity\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR)\n- Monitoring and reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing reports with financial crime enforcement agencies\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees on money laundering prevention\n- Implementing monitoring systems\n\n5. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Conducting background checks\n- Identifying potential high-risk clients\n\n6. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following national and international anti-money laundering regulations\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\nThese obligations help prevent criminal financial activities and are enforced through various laws and regulatory frameworks like the Bank Secrecy Act and Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations.",
